    "recipeInstructions": [
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "image": [
                {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    "url": "https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/QrzSaSGUqsaiS8xhJUbaI_PiJTw=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/prime-rib-roast-slow-method-995284-Ingredients1-5bb2b67d46e0fb0026296e5b.jpg"
                }
            ],
            "text": "Gather the ingredients."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "text": "The night before you&#39;re going to roast, unwrap the meat and let it sit in the refrigerator, uncovered, on a rack positioned inside a rimmed baking sheet. This will allow some of the surface moisture to evaporate, making it easier to get a beautiful brown crust when you sear it."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "text": "Three hours before you&#39;re going to roast it, take the meat out of the refrigerator and bring to room temperature. This step is important. If the meat is ice cold, the technique won&#39;t work as well. (And you don&#39;t have to worry about the meat going bad. Any surface bacteria are going to get seared immediately.)"
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "image": [
                {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    "url": "https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/Jg2Yxc1r7atndx0PQ_iEI1IYMb0=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/prime-rib-roast-slow-method-995284-Step_21-5bb2b72446e0fb0026e47796.jpg"
                }
            ],
            "text": "When ready to roast, position a rack in the center of the oven and heat to 200 F. Set your roasting pan across two burners on your stovetop over medium-high heat. Add the oil."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "image": [
                {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    "url": "https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/CoLWiyW0yD-Af21GVwZf0goILDA=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/prime-rib-roast-slow-method-995284-Step_31-5bb2b79046e0fb0026695941.jpg"
                }
            ],
            "text": "When the oil shimmers, add the roast and carefully sear it on all sides, using tongs to turn it. Sear it for a total of 7 to 8 minutes until it's nice and brown all over."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "image": [
                {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    "url": "https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/8mF59l42nxCc-KCnXt6SQp4030U=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/prime-rib-roast-slow-method-995284-Step_41-5bb2b84b46e0fb0026697a32.jpg"
                }
            ],
            "text": "Season the roast generously with salt and pepper. For a boneless prime rib, put a roasting rack in the pan and then set the roast with the fat-side up. With a bone-in prime rib, you can skip the roasting rack and set the roast bone-side down in the roasting pan."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "text": "Insert a digital probe thermometer into the deepest part of the meat, taking care not to hit bone. Set the temperature alert to beep when the meat hits 128 F (see note below)."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "image": [
                {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    "url": "https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/6qpVyBPyNTc2i-R-ddY2HJuvxHY=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/RESIZED-prime-rib-roast-slow-method-995284-Step_61-5bb2b87946e0fb0026fd769c.jpg"
                }
            ],
            "text": "Roast until the temperature reaches 128 F, which will be another 2 1/2 to 5 hours, depending on the size of your roast."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "image": [
                {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    "url": "https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/t0axcVIHIjQbRcMW6-0I4VC1_ew=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/RESIZED-prime-rib-roast-slow-method-995284-Step_71-5bb2b8b146e0fb0026c8f9e3.jpg"
                }
            ],
            "text": "Remove the roast from the oven, transfer to a cutting board, and cover it with foil. Leave the thermometer in and let the meat rest for 20 minutes."
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "image": [
                {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    "url": "https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/EYWRQZoK-LlyHpyPdro8c_DtfE0=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/prime-rib-roast-slow-method-995284-Final1-5bb2b951c9e77c0051cf5b18.jpg"
                }
            ],
            "text": "Once you take the meat out, the temperature should nudge up to 130 F, which is perfect for medium-rare, and within 20 minutes or so it will drop back down to 120 F. At that point, it's fully rested and ready to slice and serve."
        }
    ],
